segments.text: offensive and right when I was leaving you know there was kind of a you know just a change I guess it didn't seem like it may was a change that had taken place in me but some of the people that you know I would run into and stuff were just weird but I you know I don't think you can make sweeping statements like that about about an entire body of people because uh
I knew some heroes.
I knew some people who were, you know, up to speed with anybody who'd ever come to the assistance of this country in time of war, ever in the history of America.
So, I don't buy that.
I think that maybe the youth of the people might have had some effect
But most of the guys that I knew were regular people, and some of them better than regular people.
But none of them were, on the average, depraved or anything like that, like you would see in movies like Apocalypse Now and stuff like that.
Although there were the nuts.
They were there.
But they were not the, they were the exception, in my view.
An exception on it.
Oh, yeah.
How long were you over in Vietnam?
I was there a little over a year.

I stayed past the time I had to stay because they had this deal where if you had less than, I think it was seven months left in the Army when you finished your tour of duty in Vietnam, then you got out of the Army.
So I stayed there for a month or so extra and got out early.
What was it like to get on the plane and realize you were leaving that?
It was interesting.
It was good.
It was a mess, though, when I got down to Cameron Bay.
Yeah, I got out of Cameron.
I got there, and things were all screwed up, so I went and stayed at a B team right outside of Cameron Bay.
I can't remember what.
I think it was B35 or something like that.
It was at Dombatin where they had the Special Forces Jump School.
where we put the Montagnards through paratrooper training.
And I stayed there with a buddy of mine that I used to talk to on the radio all the time for about two weeks.
And then went back into Cameron Bay.
And basically, it sucked.
Because I had been out there.
It was like all of a sudden, it was like this rudely,
over-structured environment, you know, it was like he'd welcome back to the bullshit again, you know.
I had made the rank of sergeant, you know, and they treated us like a bunch of assholes at Cameron Bay.
It was more like we were just a bunch of weirdos, you know, to come down out of the jungle, and they were trying real careful to make sure that none of us, you know, freaked out.

After being in Vietnam for all that time, and all of a sudden, here I was back at Tan Son Nhat, or excuse me, Cam Ranh Bay, picking up cigarette butts, you know, and kissing ass, and getting yelled at for not having a haircut.
It just thoroughly pissed me off.
That's exactly how I felt.
I wanted to, it just thoroughly pissed me off.
And then you'd wait, you know, and wait, and wait.
And it was like a grinding kind of, you know, well, the fuck am I going to get out of here?
It was just about the way I felt by the time I left.
In other words, the processing that they put you through prior to leaving the country was sort of demeaning.
And I didn't have a weapon anymore, except, you know,
Cameron Bay was no big shake, I guess.
They got rocketed every once in a while, but it was like one big sandy bunch of bullshit.
No trees, no nothing.
And it was demeaning.
I was pissed.
And when I got back to the States, I was thoroughly pissed.
How did people treat you when you got back?
Well, again, I got out of the Army in Fort Lewis.
And I guess when you're real close to getting out of the Army, I think the Army starts to worry about you.
It's kind of like these guys are real close to getting out.
Anything could happen.
It's an explosive sort of situation, I think, because you're this close to not being in the Army anymore, and it's just kind of like you're tired of being, as they say, fucked with.
You just want out.
So we came into Fort Lewis, Washington in the middle of the night,
And the big deal was I hadn't drank fresh milk for long.
And I was dying for some milk.
And the big deal was that we were going to get steaks and milk.
So we got there in some mess hall in the middle of the night.
And they gave us these flimsy little tough ass steaks.
People were ready to throw them at the walls.
Everybody was just pissed.
I mean, we felt like we were let down right from that point while we were still in the military.
And then finally, we got out.
They hand you a plane ticket and a handful of cash and say goodbye.
It's up to you to find your way to the airport.
And you're left standing at the gate of an Army base with a handful of cash and a plane ticket.
Because what they do is they give you a plane ticket back to your home or record, wherever that might have been.
Of course, I was in New Jersey.
If you had any extra money left over,
for leave that you didn't take or whatever.
You got that cash when you got out of the service.
So here's all these lunatics, you know, standing at the gates of all these pissed off guys, right?
Standing out in front of Fort Lewis in the middle of the night with a handful of dollar bills and an airplane ticket going, ah, motherfucking shit.
And so you have to take a taxi cab, right, to the airport.
So we all got to the airport, and all special forces guys sort of stuck together.
Immediately we went to the bar and just started drinking up the bar and just going berserk.
And then said goodbye to each other.
There was this one guy, this Puerto Rican guy that I had known over in Vietnam.
But somehow or other, we got out at the same time and ran into each other at the airport.
And we flew back to New York together.
And the flight back.
That was just kind of like nothing.

The only, the worst experience I had, I came back escorting a friend of mine that had been killed, and I remember getting on an airplane that time and sitting down next to this businessman, you know, and saying, hey, I just got back from Vietnam.
And he sort of went, oh, I went back to reading this newspaper.
I was kind of like, you fucking asshole.
I felt like ripping his teeth right out of his face and sticking them up his ass.
That's pretty rude, but that's the way I felt.
And it was kind of like, the second time I came back, it was a little bit different, because I'd already been back once, you know, but the first time I came back, it was just like, strange-o.
I remember coming into the military base, and the kind of the apparent tranquility, you know, of the world,

as opposed to Vietnam, where you have like, you know, constant cacophony, you know, people yapping, and helicopters flying over all over the place, and trucks roaring and everything, and people yelling, and all of a sudden there were no barbed wire fences, and there were people in civilian clothes, and there were white people, you know, all over the place, women who weren't
and the contrast between...
I remember the first thing I thought was, God, these people do not know how good they have it.
They just don't know.
They just don't know that this is so peaceful, this is so tranquil, this is so safe.
They just don't know how good they have it.
That was my first basic impression.
The first time I came back.
The second time I came back, I was pissed.
You know, I said, I want to get out of the Army.
You know, I mean, that was just bullshit.
So, you know, I was, the second time I was, I was mad, but glad, you know.
And my family did a real nice job of greeting me.
You know, they had a big, big sign up on the house that said, welcome home.
And, uh,
It was good.
One last question.
Do you think we lost the war?
Special Forces didn't lose the war.
Maybe some other outfit did, but we did our job.
When I left Vietnam, we had, at that time, a lot of the A camps, except for the ones right on the border, either up along the DMZ or near layoffs,
were pretty much pacified.
What they did out on the A camps is they had, what they tried to do was set up what he would call, it was called CIDG, and also Ruff Puff, which were sort of like the counterpart of a home militia.
So we trained and equipped, set these people up, sort of maintained them, and when they could defend themselves, you know,
their region, you know, from insurgency, from these bozo recruiting campaigns, you know, that would sweep through their area every once in a while, and the Special Forces closed the camp down.
And when I left, there were, and it wasn't part of Nixon's Vietnamization program, it was just sort of like we had succeeded.
And when you look at the rapid deployment force that they have today that has been successful, for example, that
lightning strike they did down there in Grenada.

It was modeled after the Mike Force, which was a mobile reaction force that was, instead of going into the jungle and searching out Viet Cong and NVA, what we started to do was wait for them to attack a village or a camp.
And then we had the Mike Force, which was like the charge of the Light Brigade, which would go roar assing in there and meet them out in the open and kick the shit out of them.
And that was pretty much what we did.
And it worked to a certain extent.
And this rapid deployment force that they have now, which is basically sort of a counterinsurgency outfit, I think, is sort of designed, or what they're doing down in Guatemala

There are special forces guys down there right now training these people, and they probably have like a mobile reaction force where they wait for the guerrillas to hit the government troops, and then these guys just go tear-assing in there before they can go back and hide and meet them.
which was much more effective.

See, originally, I think, when we went to Vietnam, they did sort of traditional stuff, where they'd take 16 million Marines, give them 20 pounds of ammunition, and say, OK, march, and mow down everything in sight.
Didn't work.
So what we did was basically counterinsurgency, which had to do with waiting, laying in wait, more or less.
But also, around the A camps, they
what you would call traditional sorts of set up ambushes, sweep through the area kind of stuff.
But whenever we made contact, or whenever they made contact, and if it was sustained, there was always the likelihood that they'd call in the mobile team.
Not always, but.
I don't get it.
I appreciate it.
Sure.
